Redcoat #17 is published by Image Comics under their Ghost Machine imprint with writing credits attributed to Geoff Johns and art by Bryan Hitch, inker Andrew Currie and colourist Brad Anderson

* * *

## ‚ÄãThe Recap: The Traitor, the Genius, and the Drunk

‚ÄãIf there is one thing you can count on in the world of Ghost Machine, it‚Äôs that Simon Pure is going to make a mess of history‚Äîand look surprisingly good doing it. Redcoat #17 hit the shelves on April 15, 2026, and after what felt like an eternity of waiting (seriously, can we get these books on a monthly schedule?), I finally got my hands on it.

‚ÄãAs a fan of the "Unnamed" universe, I‚Äôve been tracking Simon‚Äôs roguish, Jack Sparrow-esque bumbling through the centuries since issue #1. This latest installment, written by Geoff Johns with the legendary Bryan Hitch on art, continues the "1909" arc. It‚Äôs an issue that trades the high-octane musket-fire of the Revolutionary War for a more cerebral, character-focused tension set in the early 20th century. Grab your tea‚Äîor something stronger if you‚Äôre Simon‚Äîand let‚Äôs break down whether this issue lives up to the hype.

‚ÄãPicking up where issue #16 left off, we find our immortal "hero" (and I use that term loosely), Simon Pure, navigating the snowy streets of turn-of-the-century Boston. He isn‚Äôt alone, though. He‚Äôs flanked by two of the most improbable companions in comic book history: a skeptical Albert Einstein and Simon‚Äôs long-time nemesis, Benedict Arnold.

‚ÄãThe core of the issue involves Benedict Arnold claiming to be a changed man. He‚Äôs dangling a massive carrot in front of Simon‚Äîthe secret ritual used by the Founding Fathers to grant immortality. Arnold insists that the key to the ritual is hidden within the historic home of Paul Revere.

‚ÄãThe trio makes their way through the city, with Einstein playing the "voice of reason" (or more accurately, the "voice of I-can't-believe-I'm-hanging-out-with-these-idiots"). The issue is light on action but heavy on historical immersion, culminating in a tense infiltration of the Revere house and a cliffhanger that suggests Arnold might not be as "reformed" as he claims.

* * *

## ‚ÄãStory and Character Dynamics

![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/e1a03337-53b7-447d-aee9-aab3c865ff96/1000014714.jpg)

‚ÄãThe real meat of Redcoat #17 isn't the plot‚Äîwhich is admittedly a bit of a slow-burn‚Äîbut the interaction between the leads. Geoff Johns is at his best when he‚Äôs writing "reluctant teams," and this triad is gold.

‚ÄãSimon Pure: He remains the "D-bag" we love to hate. His immortality has made him lazy and arrogant, yet there‚Äôs a flicker of desperation in this issue. He needs to know the truth about his power, and that vulnerability makes him more than just a walking punchline.

‚ÄãBenedict Arnold: The tension revolves entirely around his trustworthiness. Is he genuinely seeking redemption, or is this a long-con for revenge? Johns writes him with a calculated calm that perfectly offsets Simon‚Äôs impulsiveness.

‚ÄãAlbert Einstein: Acting as the audience surrogate, Einstein‚Äôs constant skepticism keeps the story grounded. His confusion over why Simon would trust the most famous traitor in American history provides some of the issue‚Äôs best dialogue.

‚ÄãThe decision to set this in 1909 Boston is a stroke of genius. It allows the series to lean into the "Unnamed" lore while keeping the stakes personal. The mystery of the clandestine cabal behind the ritual continues to loom in the background, adding a layer of cosmic dread to the historical trappings.

* * *

## ‚ÄãPacing: The "Ghost Machine" Grind

![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/6a6a15ce-d4c7-4659-9193-b51c52162170/1000014710.jpg)

‚ÄãIf there‚Äôs one legitimate grievance to air here, it‚Äôs the pacing. Redcoat #17 is very much a "middle chapter." We‚Äôve reached a point in the arc where the exposition is doing the heavy lifting. While the dialogue is snappy and the character work is solid, the narrative needle only moves a few inches.

‚ÄãAside from a pulse-pounding final page, this is a quiet issue. For readers who come for Simon‚Äôs chaotic brawls, the lack of action might be a letdown. However, if you enjoy the world-building and the historical deep-dives (like the Paul Revere backstory), you‚Äôll find plenty to chew on. Johns is clearly playing the long game here, but with the inconsistent release schedule of Ghost Machine titles lately, "the long game" can feel like a test of patience.

* * *

## ‚ÄãArt: Bryan Hitch is a Modern Master

![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/7c9850ab-703a-4440-b17b-3251dea06652/1000014713.jpg)

‚ÄãLet‚Äôs talk about the visuals, because Bryan Hitch is doing some of the best work of his career. Hitch is known for his "widescreen" cinematic style, and he brings that same scale to the intimate streets of 1909 Boston.

‚ÄãAtmosphere: The detail in the environments is immaculate. You can practically feel the bite of the Boston winter. The way Hitch renders the period-accurate architecture, particularly the Paul Revere house, makes the setting feel like a character itself.

‚ÄãFacial Expressions: Because this is a dialogue-heavy issue, the art needs to convey the unspoken tension. The side-eyes from Einstein and the smug, "trust-me" grin on Arnold‚Äôs face are perfectly captured.

‚ÄãColors & Inks: Andrew Currie‚Äôs inks provide a sharp, clean look that complements Hitch‚Äôs detailed pencils, while Brad Anderson‚Äôs colors deserve a shout-out. The palette is muted and atmospheric‚Äîlots of cool blues and greys for the snow-covered streets‚Äîwhich makes the occasional bursts of warm light from gas lamps or interior scenes pop beautifully.

If you‚Äôre looking for panels to show off the "cinematic" potential of modern comics, Hitch delivers them in spades. Every page looks like it could be a storyboard for a high-budget period drama.

