## ‚ÄãVisual Highlights

![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/7e87a3c5-6d71-4b1d-938a-d317fa30a659/1000014712.jpg)

‚ÄãFor those of us who appreciate the visual storytelling of the medium, there are three specific moments in this issue that stand out:

‚ÄãThe Splash of 1909 Boston: A gorgeous, detailed look at the city that sets the tone immediately.

‚ÄãThe Revere House Infiltration: A series of tight, claustrophobic panels that build genuine suspense as the trio searches for the hidden ritual.

‚ÄãThe Final Page Reveal: No spoilers, but the visual shift in the closing moments is a jarring, effective hook for issue #18.

* * *

## The Final Verdict

‚ÄãRedcoat #17 is a high-quality, character-driven entry that maintains the series' reputation for excellence, even if it feels a bit like it's idling in neutral. The strength of the "Simon/Arnold/Einstein" dynamic is enough to carry the weight of a slower plot, and Bryan Hitch‚Äôs art remains some of the best in the industry.

‚ÄãWhile the "Ghost Machine" delays are starting to become a meme at this point, the quality of the actual book justifies the wait. It‚Äôs smart, it‚Äôs gorgeous, and it‚Äôs building toward something that feels truly massive for the Unnamed universe.

The Bottom Line: If you‚Äôre already invested in Simon Pure‚Äôs journey, this is a must-read for the character development alone. If you‚Äôre a newcomer, you‚Äôll want to start at the beginning of the "1909" arc to fully appreciate the tension. Simon Pure might be a "tool," but he‚Äôs one of the most entertaining tools in comics today.

* * *

## 8.5/10